The Federal Government, through the Nigerian High Commission to the United Kingdom (UK), has hired lawyers to defend former Deputy Senate President Ike Ekweremadu and his wife, Beatrice, over allegation of organ harvesting, it has been learnt. Senate President Ahmad Lawan announced this after a closed-door session of the Upper Chamber yesterday in Abuja. Lawan said a delegation of the Senate will visit Ekweremadu and his wife tomorrow in London.   Bill to increase retirement age for people with disability…     Oyo students to represent Nigeria in Switzerland after…     Alleged fraud: Okorocha seeks court’s permission to travel…   The former Senate Deputy President and his wife were arrested last week and arraigned at Uxbridge Magistrates’ Court in London over allegations of organ harvesting. The court had ruled that the couple be remanded in custody till July 7, which is the next adjournment date. The visit, according to Lawan, would be undertaken by the Senate Committee on Foreign Affairs, chaired by Senator Adamu Bulkachuwa. The Senate President said during the closed-door session, the lawmakers were briefed about Ekweremadu’s travail and apprised the role the Nigerian High Commissioner to the UK, Ambassador Sarafadeen Ishola. He added that the high commissioner has been ensuring that Ekweremadu gets all necessary assistance.